{
  "buggy_files": ["fs/nfs/nfs3proc.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["nfs3_rpc_wrapper"],
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasoning": "The nfs3_rpc_wrapper function (lines 30-44 in fs/nfs/nfs3proc.c) has a critical flaw in its JUKEBOX error retry logic. When the server responds with a JUKEBOX error and the RPC wrapper calls freezable_schedule_timeout_killable_unsafe() to retry, if a fatal signal arrives during this sleep (as happens during autofs mount expiration and unmount cleanup), the function returns -ERESTARTSYS without retrying the RPC call. This causes NFS getattr to fail with error -512, leading to nfs_revalidate_inode() failure (as seen in the kernel logs: 'nfs_revalidate_inode: (0:15/6291480) getattr failed, error=-512'), which then causes nfs_lookup_revalidate() to mark the /storage inode invalid, resulting in the autofs mount being unmounted. The issue is the unconditional assignment of 'res = -ERESTARTSYS' after sleep combined with the while loop condition that exits when fatal_signal_pending() is true, causing the wrapper to return an error even though the underlying RPC infrastructure should have received a valid server reply. This is a regression from 3.14.12 to 4.1.15 related to how NFS handles server-side JUKEBOX delays in conjunction with signal-driven unmount operations in autofs scenarios."
}

